      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i checked the fuel pressure and it seems alright. could it be a vacuum leak somewhere in the intake manifold or something? how would i test for that without a smoke machine?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A vacuum leak in the intake manifold can indeed cause a lean condition, as it allows extra air into the engine. Without a smoke machine, you can still perform some basic checks to identify a potential vacuum leak. One simple method is to listen for hissing or whistling sounds coming from the engine while it's running. These sounds can indicate a leak. Additionally, you can visually inspect the intake manifold and associated hoses for any signs of damage, cracks, or loose connections. If you notice any irregularities, it might be worth having a professional mechanic take a closer look. Remember, a vacuum leak can lead to engine performance issues and even damage, so it's important to address it promptly.",
      "source": "target",
