      "role": "user",
      "content": "i tried listening for hissing but it's pretty loud in the shop so i can't really tell. is there any other way to pinpoint it? like maybe using a spray or something on the gaskets/hoses to see if the idle changes?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you're on the right track with using a spray to help identify a vacuum leak. A common method is to use a carburetor cleaner or a similar aerosol spray. Start the engine and let it idle. Then, carefully spray the suspected area with the cleaner. If there's a vacuum leak, you'll likely see a change in the engine's idle speed or a sudden increase in RPMs when you spray it. Be cautious when using this method, as spraying fuel or other liquids can be dangerous. It's also a good idea to have someone else monitor the engine while you're spraying, just in case. If you're not comfortable performing this test, or if the results are inconclusive, it's best to consult a professional mechanic who can use specialized tools to accurately diagnose the issue. Remember, dealing with vacuum leaks can be tricky, so it's important to proceed with caution.",
